qx||cs|6|fp|1|va|2|at|^-{      Defense Vs Notrump - Comments by Howard Schutzman    }
^-|cs||fp||ht|c|AT|^*B1) Comment on competing against a weak NT^*N
Howard disagrees with Cohen about the need for a penalty double over a weak NT. It is a common misconception that you can get a big score by trying to double them. In Howard's extensive experience with the weak NT, he very rarely gets a bad result when the opponents try to double his 1NT opener. Weak NTers are usually strong players and they have good runout schemes for escaping to 2 of a suit.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT|

Although there is no perfect system to combat the weak NT (which is one of the main reasons Howard plays it), Howard recommends you play natural overcalls and double as takeoutish showing a balanced hand whose minimum strength is near the top of the NT range. For example, if the NT range is 12-14 the doubler should have at least a good 13. That system works as well as any.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


AT|

Howard plays "transfer" overcalls over a weak NT, where the overcaller bids the suit below his real suit. For example, if Howard overcalls 2D over 1N, that shows hearts. This is essentially like playing natural overcalls except it gives the overcaller a little more flexibility to keep bidding with a strong or 2-suited hand (since partner can't pass the overcall).|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

Many players like to play the Cappelletti convention against a weak NT. Howard definitely recommends against playing Cappelletti and has had good success against pairs that play it. If you find it easier to play the same thing against all NT ranges, DONT works reasonably well against the weak NT (and is one of Howard's all time favorite conventions against a strong NT).|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

^*B2) Comment about balancing against 1NT^*n
If it goes 1NT-P-P-?, Howard agrees with Cohen that you should strain to balance when you have a hand with good distribution (a 6-card suit or a hand with a singleton or void). This sounds counter intuitive, but the weaker you are, the more you should want to balance. Why? Well, the points are probably evenly spread between the 2 sides. If you have a weak hand, that means partner is likely to have a strong hand. And he is sitting behind the strong opponent, meaning your finesses are going to work. Similarly, if your partner balances and you have a strong hand, don't "hang" them by bidding on. Be content to play a 2-level contract. If the opponents let you play there, you are likely to get a good result.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


